					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/drewbear" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(301632); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=301632&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610225854" alt="Drewbear" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=301632)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/drewbear" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(301632); return false;" >Drewbear</a></span> <span class="odate time_1351653216 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">31 Oct 2012 03:13</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1602630">
									

<p>The Foundation took all the bushes <em>that that guy had</em>. We know nothing about any other specimens, and I'm assuming that he couldn't have had all of them; plants have a way of escaping into the wild. :-P</p>
<p>As for the Latin America angle, I was actually thinking that it was Guatemala, which would have a higher, cooler climate closer to that that might be found in New Hampshire. I have friends that live there, and apparently they have enormous kite festivals on Dia de los Santos (same day, different name). I used Dia de los Muertos as the name so people would know that yes, this was supposed to be Halloween. Perhaps this village has a larger connection to Mexican customs than Guatemala at large. :-P</p>

							</div>

